pet forms of <i>Maud</i> (see   Maude   2) or possibly voiced variants of <i>Matte</i> and <i>Matty</i>, pet forms of   Matthew  . Compare   Madson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mattison","meanings":["English (northern): patronymic from the personal name <i>Mattie</i> (see at   Mattey  ) + <i>-son</i>. Compare   Mathieson  ,   Matson  ,   Matthewson   and   Maddison  .","Americanized form (and a very rare Swedish variant) of Swedish <b>Mattisson</b>: patronymic from the personal name <i>Mattis</i>, an equivalent of   Matthew  . This is also an Americanized form of some Danish, Norwegian, and North German cognates, most commonly   Mathiesen   and   Matthiesen  , and possibly also of the very rare Danish <b>Mattissen</b>. Compare   Matteson  .","English: variant of   Mattinson  ."]},{"name":"Maddison","meanings":["English: variant of   Madison  ."]}]},{"name":"Sidney","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which is usually said to be a Norman baronial name from <i>Saint-Denis</i> in France. However, at least in the case of the family of the poet and soldier  Sir Philip Sidney  (  1554–86 ), it appears to have a more humble origin, being derived from lands in Surrey named as the ‘wide meadow’ (Old English <i>sīdan</i> ‘wide’ (dative case) + <i>ēg</i> ‘island in a river, riverside meadow’). Evidence of use as a given name dates back to the 18th century, and the popularity of the boy's name increased considerably in the 19th century, probably due in part to  Sydney Carton , hero of  Dickens's  novel A Tale of Two Cities (  1859 ). As a girl's name it arose in part as a contracted form of   Sidony ;  coincidentally it represents an altered form of   Sindy .  In recent years, the girls' name, usually written  <b>Sydney</b> , has become popular throughout the English-speaking world, especially in North America."],"variants":[{"name":"Sydney","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Sidney .  (It was a medieval practice to write <i>y</i> for <i>i</i>, for greater clarity since <i>i</i> was easily confused with other letters.) Although traditionally a boy's name, it suddenly came into fashion as a girl's name at the beginning of the 21st century and, in this form, is now used more frequently for girls than boys in England and North America."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":69,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":78,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705206,"age":91,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705207,"age":105,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Sidney Madison was born in 1480, in England, his father, James Madison, was 30 and his mother, Jane, was 15. He married Mary Ann McMinn in England. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters."},"et":{"1480–":"1480–Surnud","1480–Male":"1480–Surnud","1500–Female":"1500–Surnud","1525–Male":"1525–Surnud","1516–1624":"1516–1624","1522–1624":"1522–1624","1450–Male":"1450–Surnud","1465–Female":"1465–Surnud","1571":"1571","1450":"1450","1480":"1480","1558":"1558","1624":"1624","1525":"1525","1479":"1479","1522":"1522","1500":"1500","1465":"1465","1585":"1585","about 1522":"umbes 1522","1516":"1516","1549":"1549","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1480–":"1480–Kuollut","1480–Male":"1480–Kuollut","1500–Female":"1500–Kuollut","1525–Male":"1525–Kuollut","1516–1624":"1516–1624","1522–1624":"1522–1624","1450–Male":"1450–Kuollut","1465–Female":"1465–Kuollut","1571":"1571","1450":"1450","1480":"1480","1558":"1558","1624":"1624","1525":"1525","1479":"1479","1522":"1522","1500":"1500","1465":"1465","1585":"1585","about 1522":"noin 1522","1516":"1516","1549":"1549","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","England":"England"},"fr":{"1480–":"1480–Décédé","1480–Male":"1480–Décédé","1500–Female":"1500–Décédée","1525–Male":"1525–Décédé","1516–1624":"1516–1624","1522–1624":"1522–1624","1450–Male":"1450–Décédé","1465–Female":"1465–Décédée","1571":"1571","1450":"1450","1480":"1480","1558":"1558","1624":"1624","1525":"1525","1479":"1479","1522":"1522","1500":"1500","1465":"1465","1585":"1585","about 1522":"environ 1522","1516":"1516","1549":"1549","Surrey, England":"Surrey, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Sidney Madison est né en 1480, à Angleterre, son père, James Madison, avait 30 ans et sa mère, Jane, avait 15 ans. Il a épousé Mary Ann McMinn à Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 2 filles."},"de":{"1480–":"1480–Verstorben","1480–Male":"1480–Verstorben","1500–Female":"1500–Verstorben","1525–Male":"1525–Verstorben","1516–1624":"1516–1624","1522–1624":"1522–1624","1450–Male"